      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: A Federal grand jury has indicted a flower grower and seven other people on charges of enslaving more than 100 undocumented workers from Mexicobeating them if they tried to escape.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: A Federal grand jury has indicted a flower grower and seven other people on charges of enslaving more than 100 undocumented workers from Mexicobeating them if they tried to escape.</p>
        <p>A Federal grand jury has indicted a flower grower and seven other people on charges of enslaving more than 100 undocumented workers from Mexicobeating them if they tried to escape.</p>
        <p>The indictment on Tuesday said the Mexicans were smuggled into the United States, then kept at the grower's 50-acre ranch until they could pay off a $435 smuggling fee.</p>
        <p>The owner of the ranch, about 50 miles northwest of Los Angeles, is Edwin M. Ives. His lawyer said he was not aware of any abuses.</p>
      </block>
